# Markdown Standards

Guidelines for consistent markdown formatting in documentation and Cursor rules.

## Formatting Requirements

### Headings
- Always include blank lines before and after headings
- Use consistent heading hierarchy (# > ## > ### > ####)
- Use descriptive, clear heading text

### Lists
- Surround lists with blank lines before and after
- Use consistent list formatting (- or * for unordered, 1. for ordered)
- Maintain proper indentation for nested lists

### Code Blocks
- Surround fenced code blocks with blank lines
- Always specify language for syntax highlighting
- Use backticks for inline code elements

### Tables
- Surround tables with blank lines before and after
- Use consistent column alignment
- Include header rows for all tables

### File Endings
- End all files with a single newline character
- Avoid trailing whitespace on lines

## Example Well-Formatted Markdown

```markdown
# Main Heading

This is a paragraph with proper spacing.

## Sub-heading

Some content here.

### List Example

- Item 1
- Item 2
- Item 3

### Code Example

```yaml
name: Example
on: push
```

### Table Example

| Column 1 | Column 2 |
|----------|----------|
| Value 1  | Value 2  |

The end.
```

## Quality Standards

- Use clear, concise language
- Maintain consistent terminology
- Include examples where helpful
- Keep line lengths reasonable (under 120 characters when possible)